sols_latex:
Our function we are considering is $\displaystyle f(x) = x^{1/3}$.
Taking derivatives gives

\begin{align*}
f'(x) &= \frac{x^{-2/3}}{3} \\
f''(x) &= \frac{-2x^{-5/3}}{9}
\end{align*}

Since the linear approximation is centred about $a = 8$ we are looking
for the maximum value of $|f''(x)| = \frac{2}{9}x^{-5/3}$ on the
interval $\displaystyle {}[7, 8]$. Since $x^{-5/3}$ is decreasing, the
maximum value is attained at $x=7$, that is, $M = |f''(7)|.$ Overall we
find that

\begin{align*}
|\mathrm{Error}| \leq \frac{1}{2}M(x-a)^2 = \frac{1}{2}\cdot \frac{2}{9} 7^{-5/3}(7-8)^2 = {\color{blue} \frac{7^{-5/3}}{9}.}
\end{align*}

